LABORATORY DATA: Lab tests done today reveals a white count of 2400, hemoglobin of 8.9 and platelet count of 52,000. Absolute neutrophil count: Segs 63%, bands 9%, lymphs 14, monos 10 and basophils 3. Chemistry reveals a BUN of 8, creatinine of 0.83 and albumin of 3.2.   PROBLEMS:  1. Mantle cell lymphoma. The patient is currently day #14, status post third cycle of chemotherapy. He has already recovered his counts. In this regard, we are planning to give him rituximab early next week and he will be admitted for the fourth cycle of chemotherapy which will be high-dose methotrexate and cytarabine in the early part right after --- Date ---. This was discussed with the patient and he is agreeable.  2. Infectious disease. There is no active infection. He is on prophylactic Levaquin and acyclovir. Since his counts have recovered, prophylatic Levaquin can be stopped right now. He will be taking his Noxafil as scheduled with keeping his interaction with vincristine in place. He was due to start with that today, which would have been about 72 hours from the last dose of vincristine.  3. Regimen-related toxicity that has been none. He has been eating and drinking fairly well. He has been maintaining his weight.   FAMILY HISTORY: No change.   SOCIAL HISTORY: No change.   CURRENT MEDICATIONS: Reviewed and updated in --- Company ---.   REVIEW OF SYSTEMS: Major issue is resolving numbness in his hands and paresthesias in his both lower extremities, which have occasionally been painful.   PHYSICAL EXAMINATION:  GENERAL: On examination, the patient is a well-built male in no obvious distress.  VITAL SIGNS: Noted. Blood pressure is 135/86, pulse 75, respirations 20. He is afebrile.  HEENT: Sclerae is anicteric, not pale. HEENT is within normal limits. There is no mucositis. There is no thrush.  NECK: Supple. Trachea is central.  LUNGS: Clear.  HEART: Sounds are normal.  ABDOMEN: Soft, nontender.  EXTREMITIES: Reveal no cyanosis, clubbing or edema. There is no skin rash.  NEUROLOGIC: He is alert and oriented x3.   LABORATORY DATA: Lab tests done today, white count of 5200, hemoglobin 12.3 and a platelet count of 177,000. LDH is 167, BUN 20, creatinine 0.97, albumin 4.1. Rest of his labs are within normal limits. A serum tryptase level was 5.7.   PROBLEMS:  1. Mantel cell lymphoma. The patient had deletion of P53 and took really long time to go into complete remission. Because of his marrow reserve at that time, a decision was made to proceed with an allogenic stem cell transplant. In that regard, he is being prepared with Zevalin followed by melphalan pre and Cytoxan post-transplant. We did a staging marrow and signed the consent with him. I had a discussion with the patient about both him and his donor being ineligible and not suitable. The patient is ineligible because of the presence of hepatitis B IgM antibody, though he does not have any viral DNA by either antigenemia or a PCR assay. That makes him ineligible, but the risk/benefit ratio favors proceeding towards the transplant. This was discussed with the patient. The potential risk of the transplant including hepatitis B reactivation and possible death were also discussed with the patient. The patient's donor is also ineligible because of his residence in Europe and we discussed with the patient the reason for donor's ineligibility for a residence in area, which in the past has been at risk for mad cow disease. The patient had several questions in terms of the risk involved and they were answered to their satisfaction. After having a thought and discussion, the patient did agree to sign the consent for the transplant.  2. Hepatitis B core antibody positivity. He is seen by Dr. --- Name ---. Since we are going to proceed with a transplant, we are going to put him on prophylaxis therapy. Initially, Baraclude was ordered for him, but there is a copay of 500 dollars, which the patient could not afford. In this regard, I gave him another prescription today of tenofovir. I have advised the patient to start as soon as it is available and we will get an idea of what copay for this would be. The patient had several questions and they were answered to his satisfaction.  3. <ADE>Peripheral neuropathy</ADE></ADVERSE> . This is probably drug induced. He is

CONTEXT STRING: year-old female with a new diagnosis of <REASON><INDICATION>anterior \nmediastinal large B cell lymphoma</INDICATION>, status post 1 cycle of chemotherapy with  R-CHOP stage II with an IPI score of 1.   PLAN:  1. The patient did not receive Neulasta after her first cycle of  chemotherapy with R-CHOP. I will check her counts in another week's time.  In the event that her counts start dropping, we might have to bring her  back for daily Neupogen. This is to prevent any delays in her  chemotherapy. She also had a most recent PET scan done, which essentially  showed hypermetabolic anterior mediastinal mass with nodal involvement from  anterolateral left lower neck and supraclavicular region of the  anteromedial left hemidiaphragm. The disease did not extend into below the  diaphragm. She had a bone marrow biopsy done, which did not reveal  involvement with lymphoma. The patient has known bulky disease. She has a  good performance status. The treatment options are either R-CHOP 3 cycles  followed by radiation or R-CHOP 6-8 cycles plus/minus radiation therapy.  However due to the B symptoms we are more inclined to give her 6 cycles  with restaging scans during tretament that 3 cycles followed by radiation  2. Neck pain: The patient has been on high-dose steroids. Unfortunately,  she has not been taking any proton pump inhibitors. I have advised her to  take Protonix 40 mg p.o. b.i.d. The epigastric discomfort, the pain when  she does not eat, and the neck pain sound more like reflux. I have advised  her that it should get better with a PPI. I have also given her a  prescription for Zofran and Reglan. In the event that her nausea and the  pain is not controlled with the above, she needs to give us a call.  3. Prophylaxis: I have given her a prescription for Bactrim 1 tablet  single strength to be taken daily for PCP prophylaxis.  4. I have advised her that in the event that she has a temperature of  100.5 or higher, she needs to call us immediately. We had a discussion  about port placement. However, the patient at this time, does not want a  port placed in. She is comfortable getting blood work done through her  peripheral veins once every week. We did discuss the benefits of having a  port including easy access, the ease of administration of chemotherapy, and  the ease of blood draws. However, currently, the patient has discussed  this with her radiologist friend and does not want to proceed with a port.   The patient was accompanied by her mother, who is a nurse and does  understand the above plan. I will bring her back in a week's time for  repeat lab draws. She will be due for her next cycle of <DRUG>R-CHOP</DRUG></REASON> , which we  will give on --- Date --- i
